(92, NULL, 16, 1, '<p>Which of the following is the correct expression for differentiating \\(f(x)=\\frac{2}{x}\\) from first principles?</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 5, 7, '<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br />\r\nRecalling the first principles formula: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{gathered} f(x)=\\frac{2}{x} \\\\ f(x+h)=\\frac{2}{x+h} \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, substituting this into first principles: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{2}{x+h}-\\frac{2}{x}}{h} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>$$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{2}{x+h}-\\frac{2}{x}}{h} $$</p>', '60', 'Easy', '1', 1, NULL, '2024-03-19 16:37:27', '2024-03-19 16:37:27'),
