(95, NULL, 16, 4, '<p>Which of the following is the correct expression for differentiating \\(f(x)=\\frac{2}{x}\\) from first principles?</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 5, 7, '<p>Solution:&nbsp;<br />\r\nRecalling the first principles formula: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} $$ For this question: $$ \\begin{gathered} f(x)=\\frac{2}{x} \\\\ f(x+h)=\\frac{2}{x+h} \\end{gathered} $$ Therefore, substituting this into first principles: $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{2}{x+h}-\\frac{2}{x}}{h} $$</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>$$ f^{\\prime}(x)=2 \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h}{x+h-x} $$</p>', '60', 'Easy', '1', 1, NULL, '2024-03-19 16:37:27', '2024-03-19 16:37:27'),
(96, NULL, 17, 1, '<p>$$ \\text { Given that } f^{\\prime}(x)=\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} \\text {, differentiate } y=\\frac{3}{x} \\text { from first principles } $$</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 5, 7, '<p>First off, we determine that: $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x) &amp; =\\frac{3}{x} \\\\ f(x+h) &amp; =\\frac{3}{x+h} \\end{aligned} $$ Then substituting this into the given formula, we aim to simplify and eventually cancel out the \\(h\\) on the denominator: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{3}{x+h}-\\frac{3}{x}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{3 x-3(x+h)}{x(x+h)}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{3 x-3 x-3 h}{h x(x+h)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3 h}{x h(x+h)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3}{x(x+h)} \\end{aligned} $$ Finally, applying our limit: $$ \\begin{gathered} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3}{x(x+h)}=-\\frac{3}{x^2} \\\\ \\therefore y^{\\prime}=-\\frac{3}{x^2} \\end{gathered} $$</p>', 'correct', '<p>$$-\\frac{3}{x^2}$$</p>', '180', 'Medium', '2', 1, NULL, '2024-03-19 16:39:42', '2024-03-19 16:39:42'),
