(116, NULL, 20, 1, '<p>$$ \\text { Differentiate } y=\\frac{1}{3 x^2} \\text { from first principles } $$</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 5, 7, '<p>First off, we determine that: $$ f(x)=\\frac{1}{3 x^2} $$ $$ \\begin{aligned} f(x+h) &amp; =\\frac{1}{3(x+h)^2} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3\\left(x^2+2 x h+h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\frac{1}{3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2} \\end{aligned} $$ Then substituting this into the given formula, we aim to simplify and eventually cancel out the \\(h\\) on the denominator: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\therefore \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)-f(x)}{h} &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{1}{3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2}-\\frac{1}{3 x^2}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{3 x^2-\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)}{3 x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)}}{h} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{3 x^2-3 x^2-6 x h-3 h^2}{3 h x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-6 x h-3 h^2}{3 h x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-3 h(2 x+h)}{3 h x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =\\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-(2 x+h)}{x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} \\end{aligned} $$Finally, applying our limit: $$ \\begin{aligned} \\lim _{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{-(2 x+h)}{x^2\\left(3 x^2+6 x h+3 h^2\\right)} &amp; =\\frac{-(2 x+0)}{x^2\\left(3 x^2+0+0\\right)} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{2 x}{3 x^4} \\\\ &amp; =-\\frac{2}{3 x^3} \\\\ \\therefore y^{\\prime}=- &amp; \\frac{2}{3 x^3} \\end{aligned} $$</p>', 'correct', '<p>$$-\\frac{2}{3x^3}$$</p>', '300', 'Hard', '3', 1, NULL, '2024-03-19 16:54:19', '2024-03-19 16:54:19'),
