(221, NULL, 45, 4, '<p>Given \\(f(x)=x^2+6 x\\), for what values of \\(x\\)&nbsp;is \\(f(x)\\)&nbsp;increasing?</p>', 'Quiz', 5, 5, 11, '<p>Solution:<br />\r\nThere are two methods we may complete this question:<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<strong><u>Method 1: Using Differentiation </u></strong><br />\r\n<br />\r\nDifferentiating \\(f(x)\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)=2 x+6 $$ If \\(f(x)\\)&nbsp;is increasing, then \\(f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0\\). Therefore, to find the domain for \\(x\\): $$ f^{\\prime}(x)&gt;0 $$$$ \\begin{gathered} 2 x+6&gt;0 \\\\ 2 x&gt;-6 \\\\ \\therefore x&gt;-3 \\end{gathered} $$<strong><u>Method 2: Sketching the graph</u></strong><br />\r\nSketching the parabola \\(y=x^2+6 x=x(x+6)\\)&nbsp;with \\(x\\)-intercepts 0 and -6:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img src=\"https://lwfiles.mycourse.app/63869eb3262971b3f737797c-public/6b78af4436d799882762be5cd54f5c7b.png\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The vertex of the parabola exists at \\(x=-3\\). As can be seen from the graph, the part of the graph to the right of the vertex is increasing.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nIn other words, the graph is increasing for the domain \\(x&gt;-3\\)</p>', 'correct', '<p>\\(x&gt;-3\\)</p>', '120', 'Hard', '1', 1, NULL, '2024-03-20 07:04:10', '2024-03-20 07:04:10'),
