(248, NULL, 50, 3, '<p>A swimming pool is being emptied for renovations. The quantity of water, \\(Q\\) litres, remaining in the pool at the time \\(t\\) minutes after it starts being drained, is given by: $$ Q(t)=3000(20-t)^2, t \\geq 0 $$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>i. How long before half of the water is removed from the pool? Give your answer correct to 1 decimal place</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nii. At what time is the water draining out the pool at a rate of \\(30000 \\mathrm{~L} /\\)minute</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[2 marks]</p>', 'Both', 5, 5, 12, '<p>i. First finding the initial volume of water in the pool by letting \\(t=0\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} Q(0) &amp; =3000(20-0)^2 \\\\ &amp; =1200000 \\end{aligned} $$ Then, letting \\(Q(t)=600000\\) [half of initial volume] and solving for \\(t\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; 600000=3000(20-t)^2 \\\\ &amp; 200=(20-t)^2 \\\\ &amp; \\sqrt{200}=20-t[\\because t&gt;0] \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=20-\\sqrt{200} \\\\ &amp; \\approx 5.9 \\text { minutes } \\\\ &amp; \\end{aligned} $$ ii. To find the rate of drainage, differentiate first: $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; Q(t)=3000(20-t)^2 \\\\ &amp; Q(t)=3000\\left(400-40 t+t^2\\right) \\\\ &amp; Q(t)=1200000-120000 t+3000 t^2 \\\\ &amp; Q^{\\prime}(t)=-120000+6000 t \\end{aligned} $$ When the rate of drainage is \\(30000 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\), then \\(Q^{\\prime}(t)=-30000\\). Note that \\(Q^{\\prime}(t)&lt;0\\) since this is a rate of decrease.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, solving for \\(t\\): $$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; -30000=-120000+6000 t \\\\ &amp; 90000=6000 t \\\\ &amp; \\therefore t=15 \\end{aligned} $$ Hence, when \\(t=15\\) minutes, the rate of drainage is \\(30000 \\mathrm{~L} / \\mathrm{min}\\)</p>', 'incorrect', '<p>part i:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$t=4.7$$</p>\r\n\r\n<p>part ii:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>$$t=18$$</p>', '360', 'Medium', '4', 1, NULL, '2024-03-20 09:43:01', '2024-03-20 09:43:01'),
